.TH HSH 1 "April 2026" "1.0" "Simple Shell Man Page"

.SH NAME
hsh \- a simple UNIX command line interpreter

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B hsh
.RI [ command ]
.RI [ arguments ]

.SH DESCRIPTION
.B hsh
is a simple UNIX command line interpreter that reads and executes commands
from standard input. It replicates basic functionality of
.B /bin/sh
and supports both interactive and non-interactive modes.

.SH USAGE
.SS Interactive Mode
In interactive mode, the shell displays a prompt and waits for the user
to type a command:

.nf
$ ./hsh
($) /bin/ls
($) exit
.fi

.SS Non-Interactive Mode
In non-interactive mode, commands are passed via pipe or file:

.nf
$ echo "/bin/ls" | ./hsh
$ cat commands_file | ./hsh
.fi

.SH BUILTINS
The following built-in commands are supported:

.TP
.B exit
Exit the shell. The exit status is that of the last command executed.

.TP
.B env
Print the current environment variables, one per line.

.SH PATH
.B hsh
uses the
.B PATH
environment variable to search for commands. Each directory in PATH
is searched in order until the command is found. If the command contains
a
.B /
it is executed directly without searching PATH.

.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Successful execution.
.TP
.B 127
Command not found.
.TP
.B other
The exit status of the last command executed.

.SH EXAMPLES
Execute a command with arguments:
.nf
($) /bin/ls -l /tmp
.fi

Search for a command using PATH:
.nf
($) ls
.fi

Print environment variables:
.nf
($) env
.fi

Exit the shell:
.nf
($) exit
.fi

.SH ERRORS
If a command is not found, an error message is printed to stderr:

.nf
./hsh: 1: command: not found
.fi

The format is:
.B argv[0]: command_number: command: not found

